#: C/network-applications.xml:637(title) 
msgid "Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP)"
msgstr ""

#: C/network-applications.xml:638(para) 
msgid "Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) is a network service that enables hosts computers to be automatically assigned with settings from a server as apposed to manually configuring each network host. Computers configured to be DHCP clients have no control over the settings they receive from the DHCP server and the configuration is transparent to the computers' user."
msgstr ""

#: C/network-applications.xml:643(para) 
msgid "The most common settings provided by a DHCP server to DHCP clients, include:"
msgstr ""

#: C/network-applications.xml:646(para) 
msgid "IP-Address and Netmask"
msgstr ""

#: C/network-applications.xml:649(para) 
msgid "DNS"
msgstr ""

#: C/network-applications.xml:652(para) 
msgid "WINS"
msgstr ""

#: C/network-applications.xml:655(para) 
msgid "However, a DHCP server can also supply configuration properties such as:"
msgstr ""

#: C/network-applications.xml:658(para) 
msgid "Host Name"
msgstr ""

#: C/network-applications.xml:661(para) 
msgid "Domain Name"
msgstr ""

#: C/network-applications.xml:664(para) 
msgid "Default Gateway"
msgstr ""

#: C/network-applications.xml:667(para) 
msgid "Time Server"
msgstr ""

#: C/network-applications.xml:670(para) 
msgid "Print Server"
msgstr ""

#: C/network-applications.xml:673(para) 
msgid "The advantage of using DHCP is that changes to the network, for example a change in the address of the DNS server, need only be changed at the DHCP server and all network hosts will be reconfigured the next time each of their DHCP clients poll the DHCP server. As an added advantage it is also easier to integrate new computers into the network as there is no need to check for the availability of an ip-address. Conflicts in ip-address allocation are also reduced."
msgstr ""

#: C/network-applications.xml:679(para) 
msgid "A DHCP server can provide configuration settings using two methods:"
msgstr ""

#: C/network-applications.xml:682(term) 
msgid "MAC Address"
msgstr ""

#: C/network-applications.xml:684(para) 
msgid "This method entails using DHCP to identify the unique hardware address of each network card connected to the network and then continuously supply a constant configuration each time the DHCP client makes a request from the DHCP server."
msgstr ""

#: C/network-applications.xml:691(term) 
msgid "Address Pool"
msgstr ""

#: C/network-applications.xml:693(para) 
msgid "This method entails defining a pool (sometimes also called a range or scope) of ip-addresses from which DHCP clients are supplied their configuration properties dynamically and on a fist come first serve basis. When a DHCP client is no longer on the network for a specified period, the configuration is expired and released back to the address pool for use by other DHCP Clients."
msgstr ""

#: C/network-applications.xml:702(para) 
msgid "Ubuntu is shipped with both DHCP server and client. The server is <application>dhcpd</application> (dynamic host configuration protocol daemon). The client provided with Ubuntu is <application>???</application> and should be installed on all computers required to be automatically configured. Both programs are easy to install and configure and will be automatically started at system boot."
msgstr ""

#: C/network-applications.xml:709(para) 
msgid "At the prompt enter the following command to install <application>dhcpd</application>:"
msgstr ""

#: C/network-applications.xml:713(command) 
msgid "sudo apt-get install dhcpd"
msgstr ""

#: C/network-applications.xml:716(para) 
msgid "You will see the following output, which explains what to do next:"
msgstr ""

#: C/network-applications.xml:717(screen) 
#, no-wrap
msgid "\nPlease note that if you are installing the DHCP server for the first\ntime you need to configure it first. Please stop (/etc/init.d/dhcp\nstop) the DHCP server daemon, edit /etc/dhcpd.conf to suit your needs\nand particular configuration, and restart the DHCP server daemon\n(/etc/init.d/dhcp start).\n\nYou also need to edit /etc/default/dhcp to specify the interfaces dhcpd\nshould listen to. By default it listens to eth0.\n\nNOTE: dhcpd's messages are being sent to syslog. Look there for\ndiagnostics messages.\n\nStarting DHCP server: dhcpd failed to start - check syslog for diagnostics.  "
msgstr ""

#: C/network-applications.xml:734(para) 
msgid "The error-message the installation ends with might be a little confusing but the following steps will help you configuring the service:"
msgstr ""

#: C/network-applications.xml:736(para) 
msgid "Most commonly what you want to do is assign IP addresses randomly. This can be done with settings as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: C/network-applications.xml:738(screen) 
#, no-wrap
msgid "\n# Sample /etc/dhcpd.conf\n# (add your comments here) \ndefault-lease-time 600;\nmax-lease-time 7200;\noption subnet-mask 255.255.255.0;\noption broadcast-address 192.168.1.255;\noption routers 192.168.1.254;\noption domain-name-servers 192.168.1.1, 192.168.1.2;\noption domain-name \"mydomain.org\";\n\nsubnet 192.168.1.0 netmask 255.255.255.0 {\nrange 192.168.1.10 192.168.1.100;\nrange 192.168.1.150 192.168.1.200;\n} "
msgstr ""

#: C/network-applications.xml:753(para) 
msgid "This will result in DHCP server giving a client an IP address from the range 192.168.1.10-192.168.1.100 or 192.168.1.150-192.168.1.200. It will lease an IP address for 600 seconds if the client doesn't ask for specific time frame. Otherwise the maximum (allowed) lease will be 7200 seconds. The server will also \"advise\" the client that it should use 255.255.255.0 as its subnet mask, 192.168.1.255 as its broadcast address, 192.168.1.254 as the router/gateway and 192.168.1.1 and 192.168.1.2 as its DNS servers."
msgstr ""

#: C/network-applications.xml:760(para) 
msgid "If you need to specify a WINS server for your Windows clients you will need to include the netbios-name-servers option e.g."
msgstr ""

#: C/network-applications.xml:762(screen) 
#, no-wrap
msgid "\noption netbios-name-servers 192.168.1.1; "
msgstr ""

#: C/network-applications.xml:764(para) 
msgid "Dhcpd configuration settings are taken from DHCP mini-HOWTO, which can be found <ulink url=\"http://www.tldp.org/HOWTO/DHCP/index.html\">here</ulink>."
msgstr ""

#: C/network-applications.xml:770(ulink) 
msgid "DHCP FAQ"
msgstr ""

#: C/network-applications.xml:776(title) 
msgid "Domain Name Servers (DNS)"
msgstr ""

#: C/network-applications.xml:777(para) 
msgid "Domain Name Server (DNS) is an Internet service that maps IP addresses and fully qualified domain names (FQDN) to one another. In this way DNS alleviates the need to remember IP addresses. Computers that run DNS are called <emphasis role=\"italics\">name servers</emphasis>. Ubuntu ships with <application>BIND</application> (Berkley Internet Naming Daemon), one of the most common programs used for maintaining a name server on GNU/Linux."
msgstr ""

#: C/network-applications.xml:787(para) 
msgid "At the prompt enter the following command to install <application>dns</application>:"
msgstr ""

#: C/network-applications.xml:790(screen) 
#, no-wrap
msgid "\nsudo apt-get install bind\n"
msgstr ""

#: C/network-applications.xml:797(para) 
msgid "The DNS configuration files are stored in <application>/etc/bind</application> directory. The primary configuration file is <application>/etc/bind/named.conf</application>. The content of default configuration file is shown below:"
msgstr ""

#: C/network-applications.xml:806(programlisting) 
#, no-wrap
msgid "\n// This is the primary configuration file for the BIND DNS server named.\n//\n// Please read /usr/share/doc/bind/README.Debian for information on the \n// structure of BIND configuration files in Debian for BIND versions 8.2.1 \n// and later, *BEFORE* you customize this configuration file.\n//\n\ninclude \"/etc/bind/named.conf.options\";\n\n// reduce log verbosity on issues outside our control\nlogging {\n\tcategory lame-servers { null; };\n\tcategory cname { null; };\n};\n\n// prime the server with knowledge of the root servers\nzone \".\" {\n        type hint;\n        file \"/etc/bind/db.root\";\n};\n\n// be authoritative for the localhost forward and reverse zones, and for\n// broadcast zones as per RFC 1912\n\nzone \"localhost\" {\n        type master;\n        file \"/etc/bind/db.local\";\n};\n\nzone \"127.in-addr.arpa\" {\n        type master;\n        file \"/etc/bind/db.127\";\n};\n\nzone \"0.in-addr.arpa\" {\n        type master;\n        file \"/etc/bind/db.0\";\n};\n\nzone \"255.in-addr.arpa\" {\n        type master;\n        file \"/etc/bind/db.255\";\n};\n\n// add local zone definitions here\ninclude \"/etc/bind/named.conf.local\";\n"
msgstr ""

#: C/network-applications.xml:856(para) 
msgid "The <application>include</application> line specifies the filename which contains the DNS options. The <application>directory</application> line in options file tells DNS where to look for files. All files DNS use will be relative to this directory."
msgstr ""

#: C/network-applications.xml:864(para) 
msgid "The file named <application>/etc/bind/db.root</application> describes the root name servers in the world. The servers change over time and must be maintained now and then."
msgstr ""

#: C/network-applications.xml:870(para) 
msgid "The <application>zone</application> section defines a master server and it is stored in a file mentioned against file tag. Every zone file contains 3 resource records (RRS): A SOA RR, A NS RR and A PTR RR. SOA is short of Start of Authority. The \"@\" is a special notation meaning the origin. NS is the Name Server RR. PTR is Domain Name Pointer. To start DNS you can run the following command:"
msgstr ""

#: C/network-applications.xml:880(command) 
msgid "sudo /etc/init.d/bind start"
msgstr ""

#: C/network-applications.xml:884(para) 
msgid "You can refer the documentation mentioned in references section for details."
msgstr ""

